<TITLE> Gastright praises Moeen's 'no politics' stance </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 19 (bdnews24.com)US deputy assistant secretary John Gastright Wednesday praised General Moeen U Ahmed and the army for not getting involved in politics. The visiting US official expressed concern over the trial of detained people charged with corruption or breaking the emergency powers rules. "I welcome General Moeen's repeated assurances that he and the army do not have any political ambitions," Gastright said in a written statement released to newspaper editors at an afternoon meeting at the home of US charge d'affaires Geeta Pasi. Earlier in the day, Gastright met chief adviser Fakruddin Ahmed and Moeen. The US embassy released the written statement based on the outcome of the meeting with the army chief. Jugantor editor Golam Sarwar, Prothom Alo editor Matiur Rahman, Samokal editor Abed Khan, Manav Jamin editor Matiur Rahman Chowdhury and New Age editor Nurul Kabir were present at the meeting. Terming the meeting with the army chief "excellent", Gastright congratulated him on the role the joint forces played in the backings of the caretaker government. "I was frank regarding our concerns, regarding human rights and due process for those detained under the state of emergencywhether on corruption charges or accused of their violations of the emergency rules," he said. Gastright made the statement at a time when two former prime ministers are in jail on corruption charges. Similarly, a number of university teachers and students are behind bars for violating the state of emergency. "We discussed ways in which our militaries can strengthen their cooperation, particularly in the war on terror," said Gastright who leaves Dhaka Thursday. bdn
